  "origin": {
    "question": "Problem 7.3. Consider the familiar metric space\\n$$\\n\\\\mathrm {d s}^{2} = \\\\mathrm {d r}^{2} + \\\\mathrm {r}^{2} \\\\mathrm {d} \\\\theta^{2}.\\n$$\\n(b) Use the results in (a) to get a first-order differential equation for $\\mathbf{r}(\\theta)$ . [That is: Eliminate $s$ as a parameter and replace by $\\theta$ ].",
    "answer": "$\\\\left(\\\\frac {\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\mathbf {r}}{\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\theta}\\\\right)^{2} + \\\\mathbf {r}^{2} = \\\\mathbf {r}^{4} / \\\\mathbf {R}_{0}^{4}.$",
    "solution": "(b) From one of the first integrals above:\\n$$\\n\\\\left(\\\\frac {\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\mathbf {r}}{\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\theta} \\\\frac {\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\theta}{\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\mathbf {s}}\\\\right)^{2} + \\\\mathbf {r}^{2} \\\\left(\\\\frac {\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\theta}{\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\mathbf {s}}\\\\right)^{2} = 1.\\n$$\\nNow substitute $\\mathrm{d}\\\\theta /\\\\mathrm{ds} = R_0 / \\\\mathrm {r}^2$ ( $R_0 = \\\\text{some constant}$ ):\\n$$\\n\\\\left(\\\\frac {\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\mathbf {r}}{\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\theta}\\\\right)^{2} + \\\\mathbf {r}^{2} = \\\\mathbf {r}^{4} / \\\\mathbf {R}_{0}^{4}.$$"
  },
